         <abstract id="aspace_f52a08941998f96e5d0c1d341bb73931">Scrapbooks of articles by the music critic Miles Kastendieck, as well as records of the Music Critics' Circle of New York City, and miscellaneous other materials.</abstract>
         <origination label="creator">
            <persname identifier="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n97861611" source="naf">
               <part>Kastendieck, Miles</part>
            </persname>
         </origination>
      </did>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_acq">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>The Miles Kastendieck Papers were established in the Gilmore Music Library by Miles and Clementine Kastendieck in 1995.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_arest">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The collection is open to researchers by appointment. There are no restricted materials in the collection. Please contact the <ref actuate="onrequest"
                 href="http://www.library.yale.edu/musiclib"
                 linkrole="text/html"
                 show="new">Special Collections staff</ref> to schedule an appointment.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <userestrict id="aspace_urest">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The Miles Kastendieck Papers are the physical property of the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library of Yale University. Copyrights belong to the composers and authors, or their legal heirs and assigns.</p>  
      </userestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_cite">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>MSS 117, The Miles Kastendieck Papers in the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library of Yale University.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <bioghist id="aspace_bh1">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Miles Merwin Kastendieck (1905-2001) was a music critic and educator. A graduate of Yale (B.A. '27, Mus.B. '28, Ph.D. '32), he wrote for the Brooklyn <emph render="italic">Eagle</emph>, New York <emph render="italic">Journal American</emph>, New York <emph render="italic">World Journal Tribune</emph>, and <emph render="italic">Christian Science Monitor</emph>. He taught English at Poly Prep Country Day School in Brooklyn, and wrote a book about the school's history, as well as a book about Thomas Campion.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_sc">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection includes Kastendieck's newspaper articles (mostly in scrapbooks), various other items by and about Kastendieck, and records of the Music Critics' Circle of New York City.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_arr1">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into 4 series: I. Scrapbooks. II. Miscellaneous. III. Dissertation-Related Materials. IV. Clippings.</p>  
      </arrangement>
